This change is a vendor-supported in-place upgrade of the existing Splunk Enterprise deployment from version 9.4.7 to version 10.2.1. The change updates the Splunk Enterprise software and bundled platform components on the current servers/nodes [search heads, indexers, cluster manager, deployer, deployment server, license manager, monitoring console, heavy forwarders, as applicable] without changing the overall system purpose, trust boundaries, or intended data flows.
No new data sources, user populations, external interfaces, or network connections are being introduced as part of this change. Existing ingestion, indexing, search, alerting, access control, and retention functions will remain materially the same after the upgrade. No new PII elements are being collected, created, or shared by this change, and there is no intended change to how PII is collected, maintained, used, or disclosed.
The purpose of the upgrade is to maintain vendor support, apply vendor fixes/security updates, and keep the Splunk Enterprise platform on a current supported release. This is a software-only update; the underlying architecture remains unchanged unless otherwise documented in implementation records.




The primary risks associated with this change are upgrade and compatibility risks rather than new privacy risks. No new sensitive data types are being introduced, and no new external data sharing is planned.
Security and operational considerations include compatibility of installed Splunk apps/add-ons and any custom scripts or integrations with Splunk Enterprise 10.2.1; temporary service interruption or reduced functionality during maintenance windows and rolling restarts; KV Store upgrade behavior and prerequisites; and the need to validate certificates, authentication, and clustered services after upgrade.
Additional implementation risks include: changes in Splunk Web runtime behavior, removal of the bundled Node.js runtime for apps that depend on it, and possible issues with configuration-management tooling if it attempts to overwrite files that Splunk now updates dynamically at runtime. There is also limited rollback flexibility, since rollback to a prior version is not a supported standard upgrade path.
These risks are mitigated through compatibility review, backups/snapshots, KV Store backup, execution during an approved maintenance window, staged validation, and post-upgrade monitoring.




Planned/completed testing for this change includes review of Splunk vendor upgrade documentation and supported upgrade path validation; compatibility review for installed apps/add-ons and custom components; backup of Splunk configuration and KV Store prior to implementation; and upgrade execution in a lower environment or pilot scope where available.
Pre- and post-upgrade validation will include service health checks, cluster/member status checks, KV Store health/status verification, authentication/access validation, certificate validation, and confirmation that core Splunk functions continue to operate as expected. Functional testing will include validation of data ingestion, indexing, searching, scheduled searches, dashboards, alerts, forwarding, and administrative access.
Post-change monitoring will include review of Splunk internal logs and health indicators for errors/warnings, confirmation of expected data flow, and standard enterprise vulnerability/compliance scanning as applicable. Any issues identified during validation will be addressed before the change is considered complete.
